('ANGELICA, WILD PARSNIP', 'Angelica archangelica', 'A. officinalis Moench, Archangelica officinalis (Moench) Hoffm.', 'Abortifacient (f; CRC); Antibacterial (1; BGB; CAN; TMA); Antiedemic\r\n(1; CAN); Antiinflammatory (1; CAN); Antispasmodic (2; BGB; CAN; CRC; KOM; PH2); Aperitif\r\n(1; BIS); Bitter (f; BGB); Calcium Antagonist (1; BGB; FNF; JAD; LAF); Carminative (1; BGB;\r\nCAN; CRC; HHB); Cholagogue (1; BGB; BIS; PH2); Cytostatic (1; PH2); Diaphoretic (f; BGB;\r\nCAN; PHR; PH2); Digestive (f; BGB); Diuretic (f; BGB; CAN; CRC; PHR; PH2); Emmenagogue\r\n(f; CRC; HHB); Expectorant (f; CAN; CRC); Fungicide (1; APA; CAN); Gastrogogue (2; BGB;\r\nKOM; PHR; PH2); Myorelaxant (1; BGB); Photocarcinogenic (1; APA); Phototoxic (1; APA; PH2);\r\nRubefacient (f; PH2); Secretagogue (2; PHR); Stimulant (f; CRC); Stomachic (f; CRC; HHB);\r\nTonic (f; BGB; HHB); Tracheorelaxant (1; BGB).', 'Anorexia (2; BIS; CAN; PHR); Arthrosis (f; APA); Asthma (1; CAN);\r\nBacteria (1; BGB; CAN; TMA); Bronchosis (f; CAN; PH2); Cancer (f; JLH); Cancer, stomach (f;\r\nAPA; CRC; JLH); Cardiopathy (1; BGB; FNF; JAD; LAF); Caries (f; CRC); Catarrh (1; CAN);\r\nCholecystosis (f; HHB); Cold (2; APA; BGB; PH2); Cough (f; APA; PH2); Cramp (2; BGB; CAN;\r\nCRC; KOM; PH2); Duodenosis (f; HHB); Dysmenorrhea (f; APA; PH2); Dyspepsia (2; BGB;\r\nCAN; CRC; PHR; PH2); Enterosis (1; BGB; CRC; HHB; PH2); Fever (2; BGB; CAN; PHR; PH2);\r\nFlatulence (2; CAN; KOM); Fullness (1; BGB); Fungus (1; APA; BGB; CAN); Gas (1; BGB;\r\nCAN; CRC; HHB); Gastrosis (2; BGB; CRC; HHB; KOM; PH2); Hepatosis (f; PH2); Hypoacidity\r\n(f; BGB); Infection (1; APA; CAN; PH2); Inflammation (1; CAN); Insomnia (f; CRC; HHB); Lice\r\n(f; PH2); Malaria (f; PH2); Mucososis (f; CAN); Mycosis (1; APA; CAN); Nephrosis (f; PH2);\r\nNeuralgia (f; CRC; HHB; PH2); Pain (f; APA; TMA); Plague (f; APA); Pleurisy (f; CAN);\r\nRespirosis (f; PH2); Rheumatism (f; APA; CRC; HHB; PH2); Stomachache (f; APA); Swelling (1;CAN); Tuberculosis (1; BGB); Tumor (f; CRC); Ulcer (f; CRC; HHB); UTI (2; PH2); Water\r\nRetention (f; BGB; CAN; CRC; PHR; PH2).', '1 tsp powdered leaf, root, or seed/cup of water (APA); 1.5 g root (1 tsp =\r\n~1.5 g)/day (BIS); 4.5 g root (BIS; KOM; PH2); 1â€“2 g root in tea 3 Ã—/day (CAN); 0.5â€“2 g powdered\r\nroot (PNC); 1â€“2 g seed day (CAN); 2â€“5 g dry leaf 3 Ã—/day (CAN); 2â€“5 ml leaf tincture (1:5 in\r\n45% alcohol) 3 Ã—/day (CAN); 0.5â€“2 ml root tincture (1:5 in 50% alcohol) 3 Ã—/day (CAN); 1.5 g\r\nroot tincture (1:5) (KOM); 2â€“5 ml leaf extract (1:1 in 25% alcohol) 3 Ã—/day (CAN); 0.2â€“5 ml root\r\nextract (1:1 in 25% alcohol) 3 Ã—/day (CAN); 2â€“4 ml liquid root extract (PNC); 2â€“4 ml liquid herb\r\nextract (PNC); wineglass of root tea (PNC).', 'Class 2b, 2d (avoid prolonged\r\nexposure to sunlight) (AHP). Contraindicated for peptic ulcer. Commission E reports photosensitivity\r\ndue to furocoumarins (AEH). Furanocoumarins may cause phototoxic dermatosis (CAN).\r\nAnticoagulant coumarins may interact with anticoagulant therapy, additively or synergistically, or\r\nperhaps even antagonistically. Angelica and root oils reported to cause photodermatosis and phototoxicity,\r\nrespectively. Root oil should be limited to 7800 ppm in skin products when the skin is\r\nto be exposed to UV. Root Oil LD50 = 2200 mg/kg orl mouse; LD50 = 1160 mg/kg orl rat (CAN);\r\ntoxic in rats 1870 mg/kg (BIS); LD50 = >5000 mg/kg top. rabbit (CAN). We may extend to all\r\napiaceous oils Bissetâ€™s comments on celeryseed oil, â€œThe drug is contraindicated in inflammation\r\nof the kidneys,â€ since apiaceous EOs may increase the inflammation as a result of epithelial irritation\r\n(BIS). Bergapten is a suspected carcinogen. Angelica root, reportedly abortifacient, should not be\r\nused in â€œpregnancy and lactation in amounts exceeding those used in foodsâ€ (CAN). Canadians\r\nlist â€œas an unacceptable non-medicinal ingredient for oral use productsâ€ (AHP). Do not use if fever,\r\nchills, headache, thirst, sweating, and a rapid pulse are present (TMA, 1996). Is this any worse\r\nthan celery, parsnip, and other furanocoumarin-containing herbs in the carrot family, even carrot\r\nitself? Until I answer this question without bias, I donâ€™t know that it deserves the low score given\r\nit by AHA. It does contain at least 15 different coumarin-like compounds, probably shared with\r\nmany other umbelliferae (Apiaceae).', 42, '', ''),
