nconcentrated root tea (PNC); 0.3â€“1 ml liquid root extract (CAN; PNC); 1.5â€“3 g fluid root extract\r\n(KOM; PIP); 2.5â€“7.5 g root tincture (KOM; PIP); 2.5â€“5 ml root tincture (CAN; PNC).', 'Class 2b. Emmenagogue and\r\nuterotonic. Contraindicated in gastric ulcers and gastrosis; not for long-term use (AHP). Commission\r\nE reports root permitted for oral use. No contraindications, adverse effects, or interactions, except for\r\nGI irritation from continued or prolonged use (AEH; KOM). The Herbal HDR cautions that overdosage\r\nleads to diarrhea, gastric complaints, nausea, and queasiness (PHR). CAN cautions that saponins\r\ncan irritate GI tract. Polygalic acid and senegin irritate the GI mucosa and may cause a reflex secretion\r\nof mucus in the bronchioles. Large doses may cause purging and vomiting (CAN).\r\nExtracts (Senega Root) â€” One antiinflammatory triterpenic acid is useful for eczema, graft\r\nrejection, multiple sclerosis, and psoriasis, according to a French patent mentioned by CAN.\r\nLooking at that suggests, to me, that the acid has immunosuppressant activity, which would be\r\ncontraindicated in most diseases. Saponins can be hemolytic and a GI irritant (CAN). Hemolytic\r\nsaponins are toxic when injected iv, but have low toxicity when given orally since they donâ€™t cross\r\nGI mucosa (CAN). Free saponins in GI tract may react with mucosa, causing an increased permeability\r\nof small intestine to intraluminal solutes and inhibiting active nutrient absorption. This\r\nactivity may facilitate entry of antigens and active food peptides into the blood circulation with\r\nadverse (and I also suppose good) side effects (CAN).', 880, '', ''),
